        <title>Socio-economic capacity building for vulnerable households and setting-up of human rights respect </title>
        <description>Burundi is gradually recovering from the war which lasted almost 15 years. With the signing of cease-fire between PALIPEHUTU-FNL and the government in 2006, there is a period of calm in all the Bujumbura rural hills. People who had moved to other neighbouring countries are gradually returning in their homes. Thus to this situation, social and economic life reconstruction becomes more and more imperative and urgent. 
In Burundi, the main income generating activity of the population is agriculture: more than 95% of people live are based on their land. Thus, the land remains the main source of income for the vast majority of households but it no longer offers to them opportunities to support their self-sufficiency following the vagaries of climate change and various plant diseases (Cassava mosaic). Add to this the looting of livestock during the war years.
The project will contribute to solve the problems mentioned above, by distributing agricultural inputs, goats for domestic livestock and the rebuilding of peace among communities. </description>
